  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I started doing USMLE after my MBBS studied 2 years at home then stopped, now after 2 more years can I start it again? I want to apply in psychiatry?",
  "response": "Restarting your preparation for the USMLE after a break is definitely feasible, but it will require dedication and a structured approach, especially given your interest in pursuing a career in psychiatry. Here's a step-by-step guide to help you get back on track:\n\n### 1. **Assess Your Current Knowledge**\n   - **Review Past Materials:** Start by going through the materials you used during your previous preparation to gauge what you remember and what you need to relearn.\n   - **Practice Tests:** Take a few practice tests to identify your strengths and weaknesses. This will help you focus your studies more effectively.\n\n### 2. **Update Your Knowledge**\n   - **Medical Knowledge:** Medicine is an ever-evolving field. Ensure you are up to date with the latest guidelines, treatments, and research, particularly in psychiatry.\n   - **USMLE Changes:** Check if there have been any changes to the USMLE format or content since you last studied.\n\n### 3. **Create a Study Plan**\n   - **Structured Schedule:** Develop a detailed study schedule that covers all necessary subjects, with a particular focus on psychiatry. Allocate time for both review and new learning.\n   - **Resources:** Choose high-yield resources. Some popular resources for USMLE Step 1 and Step 2 CK include:\n     - First Aid for the USMLE Step 1\n     - UWorld Qbank\n     - Pathoma\n     - Kaplan Videos\n     - Master the Boards: USMLE Step 2 CK (for psychiatry and other clinical subjects)\n\n### 4. **Focus on Psychiatry**\n   - **Textbooks:** Consider textbooks like Kaplan & Sadock\u2019s Synopsis of Psychiatry or DSM-5 to get a comprehensive understanding of psychiatric disorders.\n   - **Clinical Experience:** If possible, try to gain clinical experience or shadowing opportunities in psychiatry to reinforce your learning and understanding.\n\n### 5. **Join a Study Group**\n   - **Community:** Joining a study group can provide motivation and accountability. You can discuss challenging topics and share resources with peers.\n\n### 6. **Regular Self-Assessment**\n   - **Mock Exams:** Regularly take full-length practice exams under timed conditions to build endurance and improve your test-taking skills.\n   - **Adjust Your Plan:** Based on your performance in these exams, adjust your study plan as needed.\n\n### 7. **Mental and Physical Health**\n   - **Take Breaks:** Make sure to take regular breaks and rest to avoid burnout.\n   - **Healthy Lifestyle:** Maintain a healthy diet, exercise regularly, and ensure you get enough sleep.\n\n### 8. **Application Process**\n   - **Eligibility:** Confirm your eligibility for the USMLE. Ensure your medical school is listed in the World Directory of Medical Schools and that you meet other requirements.\n   - **Application:** Once you feel ready, apply for the USMLE through the appropriate channels. Keep track of deadlines and fees.\n\n### 9. **Post-USMLE Steps**\n   - **Residency:** After passing the USMLE, you'll need to prepare for the residency application process. This includes obtaining a good score on the USMLE, gathering letters of recommendation, and preparing for interviews.\n   - **Psychiatry Residency:** Research programs that are strong in psychiatry and align with your career goals.\n\n### Final Thoughts\nRestarting your USMLE preparation after a long break can be challenging, but with a well-organized plan and dedication, it's absolutely achievable. Focus particularly on psychiatry, as it is your intended specialty, and stay motivated by keeping your end goal in sight. Good luck!",
